\vspace{0.5em}
\textbf{Editorial Summary}

We present a prospective first-order behavioral simulation study of organic optoelectronic compute-in-memory inference for edge vision. Our central positive result is an Ensemble HAT training strategy that resamples device-to-device mismatch masks each epoch, raising fresh-instance accuracy from chance level (10.00\%) to 86.37$\pm$1.54\% on Tiny-ViT-5M. A profile-driven interface then translates literature-derived device assumptions into task-level risk, including a literature-anchored OPECT case study reaching 88.53$\pm$0.08\% zero-shot transfer.

We also report post-fix severe-NL retraining results that recover to the $\sim$80--82\% band, falsifying the previously reported $\sim$30\% ceiling and localizing it to a resolved software artifact. A residual gap of roughly 15~pp to the digital baseline remains, whose origin---physical limit vs algorithmic frontier---is left as an open question for future work with higher-order surrogates or measured device data.

To further anchor scope, the revision includes shared-regime sanity checks against AIHWKIT and CrossSim, and robustness sweeps under correlated device-to-device structure (86.33$\pm$1.61\% i.i.d., 84.57$\pm$2.39\% at $\rho=0.3$, 82.12$\pm$3.95\% at $\rho=0.5$; zone 3A bug-immune canonical protocol, NL=1.0, AMP disabled).

\vspace{0.5em}
\textbf{Why Nature Communications?}

This work sits at the intersection of materials science, machine learning systems, and emerging computing paradigms. We provide a PyTorch-native simulation methodology that lets materials researchers evaluate device assumptions on modern vision tasks before full hardware closure. The Ensemble HAT contribution has implications beyond organic devices, while the falsification narrative offers an unusually rigorous negative-result anchor that we believe will resonate with a broad interdisciplinary readership.

\vspace{0.5em}
\textbf{Key Contributions}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Profile-driven, PyTorch-native behavioral simulator for organic optoelectronic CIM with explicit device-profile substitution and hybrid analog/digital deployment decomposition
    \item Ensemble HAT: training-time D2D resampling raises fresh-instance accuracy from 10.00\% to 86.37$\pm$1.54\%
    \item Literature-anchored OPECT case study (88.53$\pm$0.08\% zero-shot) and severe nonlinearity localization via group-wise ablation
    \item Post-fix severe-NL retraining that recovers to the $\sim$80--82\% band, falsifying the previously reported $\sim$30\% ceiling, with a residual gap to the digital baseline whose closure awaits higher-order surrogates or measured device calibration
\end{enumerate}

